{
  "doc_id": "37048",
  "text": "It must be clearly stated that SAE is a diagnosis based on exclusion. [CITATION_1] Diagnosing SAE is challenging, especially in chronic critical illnesses. Several medical conditions must be excluded before a diagnosis of SAE can be made, including drug use, central nervous system disorders, and electrolyte disturbances. Most patients in the ICU have multiple risk factors for brain dysfunction. Consequently, the brain dysfunction associated with critical illness is often multifactorial. [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] SAE could present with symptoms that range from a few clinical findings to a coma and could entirely bypass the stage of delirium (Figure 2) . [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] Therefore, the diagnosis of SAE should not be made using the DSM IV 5 criteria for delirium or the CAM-ICU questionnaire. [CITATION_8] To date, no tool is capable of diagnosing the full spectrum of SAE.",
